{"post_stream":{"posts":[{"id":3506026,"name":"Matthew","username":"mattathan","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/mattathan/{size}/244581_2.png","created_at":"2025-02-08T18:03:59.525Z","cooked":"

Hi, we’re having issues with our CAN Bus and have no idea what is going on. Our pigeon is broken so we’ve been trying to wire our CAN. The CAN worked fine originally with just the drive train and it was working up until we added the other components to our robot. We went through every component individually, multiple times, and found that sometimes our motors on the drive train will flash orange, and sometimes it will just start flashing red and orange.
We’re using krakens and falcons frx on our swerve for the drive train. Our components on the upper half / rest of the robot are a two falcons, three neo’s, and three spark MAXs.
We went as far as to test out individual wago connectors and it’s still only working sometimes. Our programmer can’t see any of the components, finding that the CAN Bus is only working when it’s open and simply seems to stop when it gets closed again? Any solutions at all? Or ideas as to what could be wrong? We’re essentially at a standstill (and already behind by several weeks) so we’re willing to try literally anything. We can also upload photos and videos to show what we mean.

Thank you in advance!

update:all our lights are orange and signalling correct, but our programmer can’t see anything on it :((

Do you have a CAN termination resistor on both ends? RoboRIOs, PDPs/PDHs, and CANivores do termination, but if you’re using a CANivore, the other end of the line needs a 120 ohm resistor that’s not a RIO, a PDP, or a PDH

With everything plugged in and the robot powered on (DISABLED) connect a laptop directly to the first SparkMAX (using a USB-C cable) and run the REV hardware client. It will be able to see the SparkMAX you’re directly plugged into as well as any other devices it can reach on the CAN bus. You can use the “identify device” button to flash the LEDs if you’re not sure.

If you can see a few other devices but not all of them it probably indicates a crossed wire (green-to-yellow) somewhere along the chain. You can move the USB-C plug from one spark max to the next until you find the break, then take a closer look between those devices.

If a few devices are missing you might have multiple crossed wires. Follow the previous steps, then repeat until you can see everything on the CAN bus.

If you can see most devices but several are missing it might indicate a CAN ID conflict. Identify the devices with the same CAN ID, power down the robot, then reset those IDs by plugging directly into them.

If all of the above doesn’t work, I’m stumped

We figured it out! After a lot of trial and error, we discovered that our new waygos were clamping around the silicon of our CAN wires and not the actual wires themselves. It was as simple as stripping them a bit more and reconnecting them. I guess that explains the faultiness and inconsistencies, as the wires were likely reconnected slightly differently each time. A seemingly stupid fix, but everything is working now! Thank you for the lengthy response though. We did definitely try to blame it on our programmer not IDing things properly!!

With everything powered off, and no connection to the upper assembly, use a DMM to measure the resistance between the green and yellow CAN wires at the Rio. You should see something like below.

Rio only ~ 120 Ohms
Rio and PD module with termination ~ 60 Ohms

Add the upper assembly and measure again.

Full CAN system: more than 50, less than 60 Ohms

If your resistance is higher you are missing a termination, likely at your PD module. If your reliance is lower, you likely have EITHER green-yellow wires connected somewhere in your upper assembly OR too low a termination resistor somewhere.

A low value termination resistor is unlikely, but to can check just measure resistance between the CAN terminals of each device when unpowered and disconnected from the rest of the robot CAN wiring and look for something with resistance of less than 100 Ohms.

Shane
Battery Nerd
Mentor - FRC 4561, TerrorBytes
